The USP is the very definition of reliability: Iâve not had any misfeed or stovepipe with the wide variety of ammunition Iâve burned through it.  Capacity is 12 + 1âa bit small by current standards for high-capacity .45s, but the grip is not that much larger than the USP in .40 or 9mm, and feels almost perfect in my average-sized hands.  While there is holster wear evident in the matte finish, this seems significantly less than on other matte finish pistols Iâve seen exposed to the rigors of daily carry. The metal surfaces have faded uniformly from a new-in-the-box charcoal gray to a medium gray.

This particular 1999-manufactured USP 45 comes with Trijicon Orange HD night sights, light firing pin block spring, light hammer spring, and extended HK45 magazine release paddle.  I donât have the box, but I do have three factory mags, a JM kydex AIWB holster, and GG&G rail adapter to mount a flashlight or laser onto.

title: For Sale:  PC and Offers: PPS-43c w/ ammo and accessories. 2nd Gen of imports
postcontent:
Everything you see here is included. What we have here is a Polish PPS-43c. A semi-automatic "handgun" version of the famed soviet PPS-43 Sub-machine gun. These were made at the famed Radom plant in Poland, but unfortunately these are no longer being manufactured or imported and the prices are steadily rising. They are made from a combination of original PPS-43 parts and new parts.

This particular firearm is a second generation import. Unlike its predecessors, the folding stock is not welded in place, it is simply disabled mechanically and can be repaired with the stock from a parts kit and a dremel or drill to expand the hole up top for the button. The feeding issues have also been more or less corrected. This makes a great little SBR project.

This particular firearm was fired once at the factory for testing purposes before I received it (as most firearms are) but has never been shot beyond that. There is no original packaging (which was just a cardboard box) but it is essentially brand new. The moment I got my hands on it I put it into a hard case with rust preventive foam. The case itself is a hard polymer with four latches and four loops for locks, making it safe for air travel as far as I'm aware.

As you see in this picture, there are eight original magazines (four of which are loaded with 30 JHP rounds each,) a box of JHP rounds with 30 rounds still in it (for a grand total of 150 JHP rounds between the loaded mags and the box), an original sling, original cleaning rod and oil bottle and a Flambeau AR hard case with Velcro straps and magazine dividers. The dividers and straps can be removed and the straps can moved around if you so desire as the foam has factory cut outs. They were designed to hold a firearm such as an AR securely in place within the case, but I chose to use them to secure the magazines instead. All of this is included with the firearm. It has already been dis-assembled and cleaned, as well as the magazines, though I would recommend cleaning the bore again yourself before firing just for good measure. Magazines are in great condition for surplus pieces. Firearm is free of rust or corrosion apart from a very small bit beneath the folding stock that was there when I bought it.

I purchased the firearm roughly one year ago for $350 with the 4 magazines and have since then invested another $250 or so into the weapon with everything seen here with most of the extra value being in the $70 case, $104 worth of magazines,  and $60ish worth of ammunition for a total investment of nearly $600 altogether. I'm hoping to sell it for around $450 or so but before I do I'm looking for offers.

Contact regarding this firearm is not a commitment to buy or sell. This is merely an interest check and offer taking for the time being. Not accepting trades or collateral.

*If this listing is up, the stock has not yet been sold

This is a CAA Roni conversion stock/pistol chasis for Glock 17/19. This is the Gen. 2 version, NOT Gen. 1. Also, this is the model made for use with a firearm, NOT the Airsoft model. Search Amazon or whichever online marketplace you prefer for pricing on these brand new. This one in particular in NOT in new condition. There is no hard case or accessories, therefor, I am not looking to get new money or trade for it. The chasis itself is in fantastic condition, with no nicks, scrapes, gouges, or damage to the stock. It is cosmetically and functionally in great condition, however, I have never used this conversion stock and have no intention of doing so... Just not my thing. New these run about $499, I took this one in on trade and have never used it. 

Applying a pistol to this chasis falls under NFA regulation, and doing so then requires the proper tax stamp and registration of your firearm as an SBR. This is the law, and it would be YOUR responsibility to do such. These can be legally purchased without said tax stamp but tax stamp must be applied for and received BEFORE pairing with your pistol. Again, it is YOUR responsibility to do so. I am a private party, not a dealer.

Overall length under seven inches, 5.5 inches high and only 1.33 inches at its widest point, the FX45 is easy to conceal even under light clothing. But itâs a true 1911 and has all of the excellent features John Moses Browning designed into his original pistol: single-action trigger, excellent ergonomics and well-placed controls that are easy to operate.
The machined steel slide has dual sets of grasping grooves, and the ejection port has been lowered and flared to ensure that spent cases get out of the way surely and quickly.
But the most modern feature is that it uses a bushing-less barrel with a flared muzzle section. Another departure from the original is a telescoping, dual-spring recoil system on a full-length guide rod. Both of these features ensure tight and consistent barrel/slide lockup for improved accuracy and functioning. It also greatly simplifies disassemble.
The low-profile rear sight has a large, easy-to-acquire square notch and is angled to prevent it from hanging up on clothing on the draw, and its rear face is serrated to reduce glare. The front is a square blade with a white dot insert.
The alloy frame pares the Fatboy LWâs unloaded weight to a mere 22 ounces, and the frame is undercut at the trigger guard to permit a high grip on the gun.
The ambidextrous thumb safety levers are smaller than normally seen on a 1911 but can still be operated positively. An extended beavertail grip safety with a palm swell provides superior handling while ameliorating recoilâa nice feature on a .45 pistol weighing so little. Aggressively checkered, polymer grip panels allow a secure grip.

title: For Sale/Trade:  7.62x25 Pistols
location: near the continental divide, Western Slope, Colorado
postcontent:
Thinking of letting my 7.62x25's go.....would rather sell as a package then split up.

First up is my last Yugo M57, when I researched the serial date it put it 1960-1961.....no crest or manufacturer stamp just model, cal, serial number and mil inspection symbols. Importer mark is "GRC MTNBRG WV 762x25 CROATIA" Seems to be all matching with the exception of the hammer pack (has another serial chicken scratched on it). Unsafe-ties removed, I attempted fitting the import safety so it could be left in the hole but it was a lost cause and I didn't want it messing with reliability (I think I have it still in case it's wanted). Overall condition is decent (could probably pull a good rating), and has four magazines. I've put ~50 rounds through it, with zero errors (not counting my aim).

Second pistol is a Czech Vz52 (Cz-52), dated 1952. Import mark is from our friends at CAI. Seems to only have mil armorer markings not commercial ones (if I read correctly). All matching, I acquired this in an Armslist trade and was assured it was fully functional....which it wasn't. Misfed/jammed every few rounds due to a weak recoil spring and in a more detailed inspection I believed the rollers were looking a little off (seemed like they were hitting the frame). I replaced the recoil spring with a Wolff plus P and replaced the rollers and firing pin with aftermarket ones. Now it is fully functional . I do have the original parts if one wanted to reinstall them for authenticity and use it for a display/collection piece only. This one is in Good condition and also has four magazines, as well as a surplus holster and cleaning rod.

Ammo....total there is 402 rounds if I counted right, mostly new production brass non-corrosive type but ~100 are Romanian surplus.

I would like to get $800 for all of it. I'm not opposed to trades or part trades. FTF only unless you hold an FFL and want to pay shipping, and I live a couple hours from both Denver and the Springs, travel could be discussed or you can come to me. C&R items, so the only FFL we have to involve is the 03 I have (which means I need to record your info for my collection book).
